vision PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{Portsmouth F.C. Player of the Season}}\n{{Portsmouth F.C. Hall of Fame}}\n{{Exeter City F.C. managers}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blake, Noel}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Kingston, Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Sutton Coldfield Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Aston Villa F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Shrewsbury Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Birmingham City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Portsmouth F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Leeds United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stoke City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dundee F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Exeter City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Exeter City F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Pro Licence holders]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Jamaican emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Stoke City F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Blackpool F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football player-managers]]\n[[Category:Black English sportspeople]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Noel Blake\n| image          = Noel Blake.jpg\n| caption        = Blake as manager of [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]] in 2012\n| fullname       = Noel Lloyd George Blake<ref>{{Hugman|1709|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1962|1|12|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Kingston, Jamaica|Kingston]], Jamaica\n| height         = 6 ft 2 in\n| currentclub    =\n| position       = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| years1   = 1978\u20131979 |clubs1  = [[Sutton Coldfield Town F.C.|Sutton Coldfield Town]]   |caps1   =     |goals1  =\n| years2   = 1979\u20131982 |clubs2  = [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]                       |caps2   = 4   |goals2  = 0\n| years3   = 1982      |clubs3  = \u2192 [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] (loan)      |caps3   = 6   |goals3  = 0\n| years4   = 1982\u20131984 |clubs4  = [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]               |caps4   = 76  |goals4  = 5\n| years5   = 1984\u20131988 |clubs5  = [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]                         |caps5   = 144 |goals5  = 10\n| years6   = 1988\u20131990 |clubs6  = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]                   |caps6   = 51  |goals6  = 4\n| years7   = 1990\u20131992 |clubs7  = [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]                         |caps7   = 75  |goals7  = 3\n| years8   = 1992      |clubs8  = \u2192 [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] (loan)        |caps8   = 6   |goals8  = 0\n| years9   = 1992\u20131993 |clubs9  = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]                 |caps9   = 39  |goals9  = 3\n| years10  = 1993\u20131995 |clubs10 = [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]]                                 |caps10  = 54  |goals10 = 2\n| years11  = 1995\u20132001 |clubs11 = [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]]                       |caps11  = 147 |goals11 = 10\n| totalcaps = 602 | totalgoals = 37\n| manageryears1   = 2000\u20132001 | managerclubs1 = [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]]\n| manageryears2   = 2009\u20132014 | managerclubs2 = [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]]\n}}\n'''Noel Lloyd George Blake''' (born 12 January 1962) is a retired [[association football|football]]er and current coach. He was formerly the head coach of the [[England national under-19 football team]].<ref name=\"FA departure\">{{cite web|title=National Coach and Young Lions boss Noel Blake leaves|url=http://www.thefa.com/news/england/development/2014/jun/noel-blake-leaves-fa-130614|website=www.thefa.com |publisher=The FA|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> He played in [[the Football League]] for [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]], [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]], [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]], [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]], [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] and [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]], and in the [[Scottish Football League]] for [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]].<ref name=NB>{{cite web |url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player/noelblake.html |title=Noel Blake |work=UK A\u2013Z Transfers |publisher=Neil Brown |accessdate=15 May 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nBorn in [[Kingston, Jamaica]], Blake moved to England and played football with non-league side [[Sutton Coldfield Town F.C.|Sutton Coldfield Town]]. He was spotted by scouts at [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] who signed Blake a year later. He struggled to force his way into the Villa side and went out on loan to [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] in 1982. He left Villa upon his return and joined local rivals [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]. He quickly became a fan favourite with Birmingham as he scored against Villa in December 1982.<ref>{{cite web|title=Christmas Cracker 1982 \u2013 Blues 3 Villa 0|url=http://www.birminghamcity-mad.co.uk/feat/ed21/christmas_cracker_1982__blues_3__villa_0_27887/index.shtml|work=birminghamcity-mad.co.uk|accessdate=8 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe spent two years with Birmingham before signing with [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] on the south coast. Whilst he did enjoy some success at 'Pompey' winning promotion as Second Division runners-up in 1987, Blake had problems with racial abuse from his own supporters, at a time when racism was still rife in English football.<ref>{{cite news|title=Zulu warrior still fighting: Birmingham and Portsmouth legend Noel Blake relishes Fratton Park clash|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1255828/Zulu-warrior-fighting-Birmingham-Portsmouth-legend-Noel-Blake-relishes-Fratton-Park-clash.html|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=8 February 2012|location=London|first=Neil|last=Moxley|date=5 March 2010}}</ref> After making over 150 appearances with Portsmouth, Blake joined [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] on a free transfer and he helped to club to promotion as Second Division champions in the 1989\u201390 season. However his opportunities were limited the following season and so he was sold to [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] just after promotion was achieved, with [[Howard Wilkinson]] looking to spend heavily on new players to build a squad capable of competing with the very best in the First Division.<ref>{{cite web|title=Noel Blake|url=http://www.leeds-fans.org.uk/leeds/players/451.html|work=leeds-fans.org.uk|accessdate=8 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nBlake's old manager at Portsmouth [[Alan Ball, Jr.|Alan Ball]] tempted Blake to join him at [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] in 1990. Ball was sacked in February 1991 as Stoke went on to record their worst league position of 14th in the third tier. Stoke's new manager [[Lou Macari]] only used Blake sparingly and later joined [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] on loan in 1992.<ref name=NB/> He joined Bradford permanently and latter played for Scottish side [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]] before ending his playing career with [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]].<ref>Matthews, Tony: \"The Who's who of Stoke City \" (Breedon's, {{ISBN|1-85983-473-6}})</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nBlake held the position of manager of Exeter City from January 2000 until September 2001.<ref>{{cite web|title=Blake steps down at Exeter|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/e/exeter_city/1559472.stm|website=news.bbc.co.uk |publisher=BBC|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nA qualified coach and holder of the [[UEFA Pro Licence]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/6376121.stm |title=Focus: Football's black mark  |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=22 February 2007 |first=Simon |last=Austin |accessdate=15 May 2009}}</ref> Blake was appointed in February 2007 as one of [[the Football Association]]'s National Coaches to work with players in [[England national football team|England]]'s youth teams and to assist with coach education.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/MensUnder19s/NewsAndFeatures/2007/NoelBlakeAppointment.aspx |title=Noel Blake on board |date=12 February 2007 |accessdate=15 May 2009 |publisher=[[The Football Association]]}}</ref> He was placed in charge of the England under-19 team in 2009, leading the side to the semi-finals of the [[UEFA European Under-19 Championship]] in both [[2010 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|2010]] and [[2012 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|2012]] before leaving the Football Association in June 2014.<ref name=\"FA departure\"/>\n\nOn 1 July it was reported that Blake was about to become first-team coach at [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]].<ref name=gazette6703238>{{cite web|title=England coach set for Pool|url=http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/sport/blackpool-fc/england-coach-set-for-pool-1-6703238|publisher=[[Blackpool Gazette]]|accessdate=1 July 2014|date=1 July 2014}}</ref> On 27 October Blake was put in temporary charge following the departure of [[Jose Riga]].<ref name=BBC>{{cite web|title=Jose Riga: Championship strugglers Blackpool sack manager |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/29795449|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=27 Oct 2014|date=27 Oct 2014}}</ref> He left Blackpool in December 2014.\n\n==Personal life==\nBlake suffered a [[stroke]] in August 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Noel Blake opens up about emotional trauma after suffering stroke|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-Noel-Blake-opens-emotional-trauma/story-29346832-detail/story.html|website=Stoke Sentinel|accessdate=6 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n; Portsmouth \n* [[Football League Second Division]] runner-up: [[1986\u201387 in English football|1986\u201387]]\n\n==Career statistics==\n===As a player===\n*Sourced from [http://www.enfa.co.uk/ The English National Football Archive]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: 