{"title_page": "Stucky (fandom)", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n[[File:Gwenpool Stucky Panel.png|thumb|upright=2|right|An exchange from ''[[Gwenpool|Gwenpool Strikes Back]]'' #3 (2019) interpreted by commentators as a humorous acknowledgement of the Stucky fandom by Marvel.<ref name=\"GWENPOOL\"/>|alt=Comic panel from \"Gwenpool Strikes Back\" #3 featuring Steve Rogers and Bucky Barnes.]]\n\n'''Stucky''', also '''Steve/Bucky''' or '''Bucky/Steve''',{{efn|The ship names '''Wintershield''', '''Starbucks''', and '''Barnes & Noble''' are also occasionally used.<ref name=\"MarySue1\"/>}} is the [[Shipping (fandom)|ship name]] given to the [[Slash fiction|slash]] pairing of [[Captain America|Steve Rogers]] ([[Captain America]]) and [[Bucky Barnes]] (the [[Bucky Barnes|Winter Soldier]]),{{efn|Per [[Shipping (fandom)#Naming conventions|shipping naming conventions]], Stucky is a [[portmanteau]] of \"Steve\" and \"Bucky\".<ref name=\"TRASH\"/>}} fictional characters appearing in [[American comic book|comic books]] and related media produced by [[Marvel Comics]]. Though Rogers and Barnes have appeared in media dating to the 1940s, [[Fan labor|fan works]] depicting a romantic or sexual relationship between the characters grew substantially in popularity in the 2010s following their appearances in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] (MCU). Several individuals associated with Marvel, including Winter Soldier co-creator [[Ed Brubaker]], Barnes' actor [[Sebastian Stan]], and MCU director [[Russo brothers|Joe Russo]], have commented positively on Stucky. Critics and commentators have used the popularity of Stucky in [[fandom]] to remark on a range of topics, including the lack of [[LGBT]] characters in [[superhero films]] and the nature of fandom on social media.\n\n==Background==\n===Marvel Comics===\n[[Captain America|Steve Rogers]] and [[Bucky Barnes]] first appeared in ''[[Captain America#Golden Age|Captain America Comics]]'' #1 (March 1941), which establishes Rogers as Captain America and Barnes as his teenaged [[sidekick]]. Barnes would be killed in 1948 and would not re-appear until [[Captain America (vol. 5)|''Captain America'' (vol. 5)]] in 2005, where the character is [[comic book death|brought back from supposed death]] as the Winter Soldier, a brainwashed assassin.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hall |first1=Richard |title=The American Superhero: Encyclopedia of Caped Crusaders in History |publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]] |location=Santa Barbara, California |isbn=978-1440861239 |page=102}}</ref> As a result of Barnes' extended absence from comics, and Rogers' initial characterization as a much older [[paternal]] figure to Barnes, the emergence of Stucky as a phenomenon in [[fandom]] is a relatively recent development;<ref name=\"POLY1\"/> in pre-social media [[Shipping (fandom)|shipping]] fandom of the early 2000s, Rogers was most commonly depicted with [[Tony Stark]] ([[Iron Man]]), the pairing typically abbreviated as \"Stony\" or \"Superhusbands\".<ref name=\"POLY1\"/>{{sfn|Coker|2013|pp=1.8}}\n\nWhile hero-and-sidekick relationships in comics are frequently interpreted as having a [[homoerotic]] subtext \u2014 an argument infamously made by [[Fredric Wertham]] in his 1954 book ''[[Seduction of the Innocent]]'', which asserted that [[Batman]] and [[Robin (character)|Robin]]'s relationship promotes homosexuality and pederasty \u2014 in Marvel [[Canon (fiction)|canon]], the relationship between Rogers and Barnes is strictly platonic, and is not depicted as sexual or romantic.{{sfn|Gillen|2009|pp=109}} Regardless, Rogers and Barnes are consistently depicted in-canon as having a deep and meaningful personal bond, with some critics likening their relationship as wartime compatriots to [[Achilles and Patroclus]].{{sfn|Gillen|2009|pp=109}}\n\n===Marvel Cinematic Universe===\n{{See also|Steve Rogers (Marvel Cinematic Universe)}}\n{{multiple image\n | width1 = 120\n | image1 = Chris Evans - Captain America 2 press conference (cropped2).jpg\n | alt1 = Actor Chris Evans at a press conference in 2014.\n | image2 = Sebastian Stan by Gage Skidmore 2 (cropped).jpg\n | width2 = 120\n | alt2 = Actor Sebastian Stan at San Diego Comic-Con International in 2019.\n | footer = Actors [[Chris Evans (actor)|Chris Evans]] (left) and [[Sebastian Stan]] (right), who portray Steve Rogers and Bucky Barnes, respectively, in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] (MCU).\n}}\n\nThe popularity of Stucky as a ship in fandom rose substantially following the introduction of Rogers and Barnes to the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] (MCU),<ref name=\"POLY1\"/> where they have jointly appeared in five films: ''[[Captain America: The First Avenger]]'' (2011), ''[[Captain America: The Winter Soldier]]'' (2014), ''[[Captain America: Civil War]]'' (2016), ''[[Avengers: Infinity War]]'' (2018), and ''[[Avengers: Endgame]]'' (2019). The films re-conceptualize the nature of Rogers' and Barnes' relationship, presenting them as same-age lifelong best friends,<ref name=\"POLY1\"/>{{sfn|Coker|2013|pp=1.7}} and establish their bond as a key plot element and mutual character motivation.<ref name=\"DOT\"/><ref name=\"POLY2\"/> As a result, a fandom developed in reaction to a supposed homoerotic subtext to Rogers' and Barnes' relationship.<ref name=\"VF1\"/><ref name=\"MTV\"/>\n\nAcross the ''Captain America'' trilogy of films, Gavia Baker-Whitelaw of ''[[The Daily Dot]]'' notes that Rogers continually \"rebel[s] against authority for the sake of Bucky's wellbeing, escalating from disobeying orders in [[World War II]], to becoming an international fugitive in ''Civil War''.\"<ref name=\"DOT\"/> The relationship serves as the driving plot to ''The Winter Soldier'', where Barnes' memory of Rogers causes him to overcome his conditioning as a brainwashed assassin;<ref name=\"MTV\"/> Barnes recalls his identity through Rogers' declaration of \"I'm with you till the end of the line\", a phrase repeated by Rogers and Barnes throughout the series as an expression of kinship.<ref name=\"SR\"/> Their relationship is again a central plot element in ''Civil War'', as Rogers protects Barnes after he is wrongly accused of committing a terrorist act.<ref name=\"BEAST\"/> That film also develops [[Sharon Carter]] as a love interest for Rogers; writing for ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', Joanna Robinson called the development the \"one flaw in the otherwise great\" film, arguing that the film's kiss between Rogers and Carter exists primarily to \"put the nail in the coffin of speculation\" around a homoerotic interpretation of Rogers' and Barnes' relationship.<ref name=\"VF2\"/> While Rogers and Barnes appear in both ''Infinity War'' and ''Endgame'', comparably less time is spent on developing their relationship,<ref name=\"BUSTLE\"/><ref name=\"CB1\"/> with Robinson and other critics hypothesizing that their interactions were minimized to build popularity for [[Falcon (comics)|Sam Wilson]] ([[Falcon (comics)|Falcon]]) as he assumes the mantle of Captain America, and to emphasize the canonical love story between Rogers and [[Peggy Carter]].<ref name=\"VF1\"/><ref name=\"DOG\"/><ref name=\"BEAT\"/>\n\n==Analysis and impact==\nStucky as a phenomenon in [[fandom]] emerged from online communities that produce [[Fan labor|fan works]]. These online communities are typically majority female, in contrast to the majority male mainstream comics fandom.{{sfn|Coker|2013|pp=1.1}} Fan works featuring Stucky cover a wide range of mediums, including [[fan art]], [[fanfiction]], and [[Vidding|fan videos]], and typically give prominence to emotional imagery and romantic subject material, as opposed to the action- and conflict-centered narratives of Marvel's comic and film source material.{{sfn|Coker|2013|pp=1.1}}{{sfn|Coppa|2017|pp=220}} Stucky fan works thus \"realize all the un-filmed narrative moments that fans want to see,\"{{sfn|Coppa|2017|pp=226}} with depictions of Rogers' and Barnes' domestic life in 1940s New York \u2013 largely unexplored in canonical source material \u2013 being a common trope in Stucky fan works.<ref name=\"MARYSUE\"/> In lieu of canonical material than can be drawn from, these particular works often maintain a high degree of historical fidelity; ''Gay New York'', a sociological text by LGBT historian [[George Chauncey]], is noted as having been utilized by some fan creators to accurately depict aspects of [[LGBT history in New York#1900\u20131949|pre-war gay culture in New York City]], including real-life period-specific [[gay bar]]s that existed in Rogers' canonical Brooklyn neighborhood.<ref name=\"MARYSUE\"/>{{sfn|Coppa|2017|pp=224}}\n\nIn ''Captain America, Masculinity, and Violence: The Evolution of a National Icon'', author J. Richard Stevens argues that fans of Captain America use the character \"to reconstruct and reconfigure cultural significance in their own lives,\"{{sfn|Stevens|2015|pp=10}} noting that \"throughout the character's history, which contains messages from ultranationalist [[jingoism]] to a critique of the role of [[nationalism]] in the propagation of racism and terrorism, his narratives have provoked incredibly articulate responses.\"{{sfn|Stevens|2015|pp=2}} In the specific case of Stucky, Francesca Coppa argues that the fandom is a response to the unlikelihood of Marvel acknowledging a queer reading of Rogers' and Barnes' relationship in canon, and a desire by some fans to formulate what such an acknowledgement could look like.{{sfn|Coppa|2017|pp=226}} Thus, Stucky represents both the [[objectification]] and [[Subjectification (linguistics)|subjectification]] of Steve Rogers as character, \"with fans writing stories that flesh out his politics, his relationships past and present, his religion, and his sexuality.\"{{sfn|Coppa|2017|pp=223}} In this regard, Stucky as a phenomenon in [[Shipping (fandom)|shipping]] is notable in that it devotes significant focus to the characters' imagined homosexuality or bisexuality,{{sfn|Coppa|2017|pp=224}} in contrast to [[Slash fiction|slash fan works]] of the 1970s and 1980s that \"distanc[ed] beloved characters from the stereotypes and even the identity of gayness,\" opting to instead depict the characters as \"sharing a great, transcendent love that eliminated the boundaries of gender.\"{{sfn|Coker|2013|pp=1.9}}\n\nThe popularity of Stucky in fandom has been widely commented on by mainstream pop culture and entertainment sources.<ref name=\"SR\"/><ref name=\"MARYSUE\"/>{{sfn|Coppa|2017|pp=225}} In [[Tumblr]]'s annual rankings of the most popular ships of the year (as measured by number of [[Reblogging|reblogs]]), Stucky placed 17th in 2014,<ref>{{cite web |title=Most Reblogged Ships |url=https://2014inreblogs.tumblr.com/post/133384976809/most-reblogged-ships-ship-noun-short-for |website=2014 Tumblr Year in Review |publisher=[[Tumblr]] |accessdate=29 October 2019 |date=17 November 2014}}</ref> 9th in 2015,<ref>{{cite web |title=Most Reblogged Ships |url=https://yearinreview.tumblr.com/post/134751774307/most-reblogged-ships |website=Tumblr 2015 Year in Review |publisher=[[Tumblr]] |accessdate=29 October 2019 |date=7 December 2015}}</ref> 8th in 2016,<ref>{{cite web |title=2016\u2019s Top Ships |url=https://fandom.tumblr.com/post/153998280734/ships |website=Fandom on Tumblr |publisher=[[Tumblr]] |accessdate=29 October 2019 |date=3 December 2016}}</ref> 10th in 2018,<ref>{{cite web |title=2018\u2019s Top Ships |url=https://fandom.tumblr.com/post/180587157919/2018-ships |website=Fandom on Tumblr |publisher=[[Tumblr]] |accessdate=29 October 2019 |date=28 November 2018}}</ref> and 16th in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=2019\u2019s Top 100 Ships |url=https://fandom.tumblr.com/post/189431747929/2019-ships |website=Fandom on Tumblr |publisher=[[Tumblr]] |accessdate=7 December 2019 |date=2 December 2019}}</ref> Over 45,000 Stucky fan works have been published on [[Archive of Our Own]], making Stucky among the most popular ships on the website.<ref>{{cite web |title=James \"Bucky\" Barnes/Steve Rogers |url=https://archiveofourown.org/tags/James%20%22Bucky%22%20Barnes*s*Steve%20Rogers/works |website=[[Archive of Our Own]] |accessdate=26 November 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191123011829/https://archiveofourown.org/tags/James%20%22Bucky%22%20Barnes*s*Steve%20Rogers/works |archivedate=23 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===#GiveCaptainAmericaABoyfriend===\nIn May 2016, [[Twitter]] user Jess Salerno tweeted \"#givecaptainamericaaboyfriend\" in response to a similar [[Internet activism|internet campaign]] around the [[hashtag]] #GiveElsaAGirlfriend, which focused on [[Elsa (Frozen)|Elsa]] from the 2013 film ''[[Frozen (2013 film)|Frozen]]''.<ref name=\"MetroUK\"/><ref name=\"Kotaku1\"/> The hashtag became a viral [[Twitter trends|trending topic]] on Twitter,<ref name=\"Wrap\"/> and was widely covered by the mainstream press.<ref name=\"MetroUK\"/><ref name=\"EW\"/><ref name=\"AP\"/><ref name=\"WAPO\"/><ref name=\"TIME\"/> While the hashtag was ostensibly organized around fans who wished to see Stucky made canon, both it and #GiveElsaAGirlfriend were also broadly concerned with the lack of LGBT characters in media properties owned by [[Disney]], of which Marvel is a subsidiary.<ref name=\"Crush\"/><ref name=\"IO9\"/> The LGBT rights organization [[GLAAD]] commented that the hashtag was \"a sign that audiences are eager for significant LGBT characters in their superhero movies.\"<ref name=\"AP\"/>\n\n''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' cited #GiveCaptainAmericaABoyfriend as an example of how social media has altered the dynamic between creators and audiences, as the medium increases both the visibility of fan discussions and the willingness of creators to respond to these discussions.<ref name=\"THR\"/> In the specific case of #GiveCaptainAmericaABoyfriend, ''The Hollywood Reporter'' noted that the campaign \"highlights demographic shifts that have yet to be reflected in the texts audiences are responding to,\" in reference to the popularity of Stucky relative to the lack of LGBT characters in superhero films.<ref name=\"THR\"/>\n\n==Response==\n{{Rquote |1=right |2= What\u2019s fascinating about the Cap-Bucky story as well is it\u2019s a love story. These are two guys who grew up together, and so they have that same emotional connection to each other as brothers would, and even more so because Bucky was all Steve had growing up. |3=[[Russo brothers|Joe Russo]] |4=<br>Marvel Cinematic Universe director<ref name=\"EMPIRE\"/>}}\n\nSeveral individuals affiliated with Marvel have commented on Stucky, frequently in a context that affirms Rogers' and Barnes' canonical heterosexuality while offering support for the broader Stucky fandom.\n\nRogers' actor [[Chris Evans (actor)|Chris Evans]] has commented positively on romantic interpretations on Rogers' relationship with Barnes, though qualified that \"it's just never been part of my approach to the character.\"<ref name=\"POLY2\"/><ref name=\"MYTH\"/> When asked about Stucky in a separate interview interview with ''[[GQ]]'', Barnes' actor [[Sebastian Stan]] similarly responded that \"I think it's great. Movies are for people to relate to in whatever way they want,\" adding that \"I don't think of the character that way, though. But there's no right or wrong answer.\"<ref name=\"GQ\"/> Evans has separately remarked that Barnes is \"one of the more precious relationships for Steve Rogers [...] it's one of the few relationships that he can identify as anything we would call home,\"<ref name=\"MOVIEFONE\"/> which has been quoted by outlets in the context of their coverage of Stucky.<ref name=\"VF1\"/><ref name=\"MOVIEFONE\"/><ref name=\"BUZZFEED1\"/> An image from a fan [[photo op]] of Evans and Stan at [[Wizard World Philadelphia]] posing with [[cosplay]]ers kissing while dressed as Rogers and Barnes went viral in 2016.<ref name=\"IO9\"/><ref name=\"OW\"/>\n\n[[Russo brothers|Joe Russo]], who co-directed four of the five MCU films in which Rogers and Barnes jointly appear, has described their relationship as a love story,<ref name=\"EMPIRE\"/> later stating that \"people have interpreted that relationship all kinds of ways, and it's great to see people argue about it what that relationship means to them. We will never define it as filmmakers, explicitly, but however people want to interpret it, they can interpret it.\"<ref name=\"VF1\"/><ref name=\"MTV\"/> Screenwriters [[Christopher Markus and Stephen McFeely]], who jointly wrote the ''Captain America'' film trilogy, ''Infinity War'', and ''Endgame'', likened Rogers and Barnes' relationship to a love story and described the characters as soulmates in the foreword of the [[Trade paperback (comics)|trade paperback]] edition of the comic book series ''[[Captain America: White]]''.<ref name=HCForeward>{{cite book|contributor-last1=Markus|contributor-first1=Christopher|contributor-last2=McFeely|contributor-first2=Stephen|contribution=Introduction |date=2016|title=Captain America: White|last1=Loeb|first1=Jeph | publisher=Marvel Comics|isbn=978-0785133766|ref=harv|pages=1\u20132}}</ref>\n\nOther individuals who have remarked positively on Stucky include writers [[Ed Brubaker]], who co-created the Winter Soldier with artist [[Steve Epting]],<ref name=\"BC\"/> and [[Mark Waid]], who remarked in an interview with Marvel regarding his 2016 run on the comic book series ''[[Black Widow (Marvel Comics)|Black Widow]]'' that both Black Widow and Barnes \"have had a crush\" on Steve Rogers.<ref name=\"WAID\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kirk/Spock]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite web |last1=Bahr |first1=Lindsey |title=GLAAD responds to #GiveCaptainAmericaABoyfriend |url=http://apnews.com/8957b80de9f444b7bc7f91ecc8184cb7 |website=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=8 November 2019 |date=25 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BEAST\">{{cite web |last1=Yamato |first1=Jen |title=\u2018Captain America: Civil War\u2019 Star Sebastian Stan on Whether Bucky and Cap Are in Love |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/captain-america-civil-war-star-sebastian-stan-on-whether-bucky-and-cap-are-in-love |website=[[The Daily Beast]] |accessdate=7 November 2019 |date=9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BEAT\">{{cite web |last1=Steele |first1=Amanda |title=Queer Coding Bucky Barnes: Why the MCU Should Put Up |url=https://www.comicsbeat.com/bucky-barnes-queer-coding/ |website=[[Comics Beat]] |accessdate=8 November 2019 |date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=BC>{{cite web\n |url= https://www.bleedingcool.com/2016/05/27/ed-brubaker-talks-captain-america/\n |title= Ed Brubaker Talks Captain America. Or Not.\n |last= Johnson\n |first= Rich\n |date= 27 May 2016\n |work= [[Bleeding Cool]]\n |access-date= 28 October 2019\n }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BUSTLE\">{{cite web |last1=Florio |first1=Angelica |title=The Lack Of Stucky Moments In \u2018Endgame\u2019 Has Steve & Bucky Shippers In Their Feelings |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/the-lack-of-stucky-moments-in-endgame-has-steve-bucky-shippers-in-their-feelings-17227283 |website=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |accessdate=7 November 2019 |date=26 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BUZZFEED1\">{{cite web |last1=Wieselman |first1=Jarett |title=Chris Evans Has A Theory Why Fans Love His Relationship With Bucky So Much |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/jarettwieselman/bucky-loves-steve-and-steve-loves-bucky#.rlM8bGDkDW |website=[[Buzzfeed]] |accessdate=7 November 2019 |date=17 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CB1\">{{cite web |last1=Peters |first1=Megan |title=The Internet Has Lots to Say About Bucky and Captain America\u2019s \u2018Infinity War\u2019 Reunion |url=https://comicbook.com/marvel/2018/04/29/avengers-infinity-war-captain-american-bucky-barnes-stucky-react/ |website=ComicBook.com |accessdate=7 November 2019 |date=11 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Crush\">{{cite web |last1=Hayes |first1=Britt |title=New \u2018Infinity War\u2019 Spot Gives Stucky \u2019Shippers a New Hope |url=https://screencrush.com/infinity-war-stucky-shippers/ |website=[[Screen Crush]] |accessdate=7 November 2019 |date=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DOG\">{{cite web |last1=Burt |first1=Kayti |title=Why Avengers: Endgame's Sidelining of the Steve & Bucky Relationship Matters |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/280702/why-avengers-endgame-sidelining-stucky-matters |website=[[Den of Geek]] |accessdate=8 November 2019 |date=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=DOT>{{cite web\n |url= https://www.dailydot.com/parsec/avengers-endgame-heteronormative-steve-bucky/\n |title= How the straight agenda ruined \u2018Avengers: Endgame\u2019 \n |last= Baker-Whitelaw\n |first= Gavia\n |date= 10 May 2019\n |work= [[The Daily Dot]]\n |access-date= 29 October 2019\n }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=EMPIRE>{{cite web\n |url= https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/captain-america-civil-war-love-story-says-joe-russo/\n |title= Captain America: Civil War is a love story, says Joe Russo\n |last= De Semlyen\n |first= Phil\n |date= 22 March 2016\n |work= [[Empire Magazine]]\n |access-date= 30 October 2019\n }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite web |last1=Nolfi |first1=Joey |title=#GiveCaptainAmericaABoyfriend campaign goes viral on Twitter |url=https://ew.com/article/2016/05/24/captain-america-boyfriend-twitter-campaign/ |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=8 November 2019 |date=24 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=GQ>{{cite web\n |url= https://www.gq.com/story/sebastian-stan-style-interview\n |title= Sebastian Stan on Social Media, Style, and Life After ''Captain America''\n |last= Berlinger\n |first= Max\n |date= 16 May 2016\n |work= [[GQ]]\n |access-date= 28 October 2019\n }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"GWENPOOL\">{{cite web |last1=Dyce |first1=Andrew |title=Captain America/Bucky Fanfic Exists in Marvel's Universe, Too |url=https://screenrant.com/captain-america-bucky-fanfiction-marvel-comic/ |website=[[Screen Rant]] |accessdate=9 November 2019 |date=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"IO9\">{{cite web |last1=Whitbrook |first1=James |title=Captain America and Winter Soldier Make Out as Chris Evans and Sebastian Stan Look on Approvingly |url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/captain-america-and-winter-soldier-make-out-as-chris-ev-1781261333 |website=[[io9]] |publisher=[[G/O Media]] |accessdate=7 November 2019 |date=8 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Kotaku1\">{{cite web |last1=Jackson |first1=Gita |title=Shipping, Explained |url=https://kotaku.com/shipping-explained-1821927276 |website=[[Kotaku]] |accessdate=7 November 2019 |date=23 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MARYSUE\">{{cite web |last1=Hale-Stern |first1=Kaila |title=Steve Rogers/Bucky Barnes Is the Most Popular MCU Ship Ever |url=https://www.themarysue.com/steve-bucky-the-mcu-mothership/ |website=[[The Mary Sue]] |accessdate=8 November 2019 |date=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MarySue1\">{{cite web |last1=Lachenal |first1=Jessica |title=Joe Russo Calls Captain America: Civil War a \"Love Story\" Between Cap and Bucky |url=https://www.themarysue.com/stucky-lives-maybe/ |website=[[The Mary Sue]] |accessdate=23 December 2019 |date=22 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MetroUK\">{{cite web |last1=Flint |first1=Hannah |title=People are sharing why Marvel should #GiveCaptainAmericaABoyfriend |url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/05/24/people-are-sharing-why-marvel-should-givecaptainamericaaboyfriend-5901124#ixzz49eKzSmHY |website=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro UK]] |accessdate=8 November 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029005759/https://metro.co.uk/2016/05/24/people-are-sharing-why-marvel-should-givecaptainamericaaboyfriend-5901124/ |archivedate=29 October 2016 |date=24 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MOVIEFONE\">{{cite web |last1=Carbone |first1=Gina |title=Chris Evans Clarifies That 'Avengers 4' Tweet, Gives Big Bucky Tease |url=https://www.moviefone.com/2018/10/15/chris-evans-clarifies-that-avengers-4-tweet-gives-big-bucky-tease/ |website=[[Moviefone]] |accessdate=7 November 2019 |date=15 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MTV\">{{cite web |last1=Bell |first1=Crystal |title='Captain America' Director Is Totally Down With Your Steve And Bucky Shipping |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2718101/captain-america-steve-bucky-shipping/ |website=[[MTV]] |accessdate=7 November 2019 |date=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MYTH\">{{cite web |last1=Davis |first1=Oli |title=Is Captain America in love with Bucky Barnes? Chris Evans talks about Steve Rogers\u2019 sexuality |url=https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2016/05/is-captain-america-in-love-with-bucky-barnes-chris-evans-clears-up-steve-rogers-sexuality/ |website=Flickering Myth |accessdate=8 November 2019 |date=1 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"OW\">{{cite web |last1=Tracey |first1=Janet |title=Chris Evans and Sebastian Stan Meet Stucky Cosplayers at Wizard World Philadelphia |url=https://www.outerplaces.com/science-fiction/item/12369-chris-evans-and-sebastian-stan-meet-stucky-cosplayers-at-wizard-world-philadelphia |website=Outer Worlds |accessdate=7 November 2019 |date=8 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=POLY1>{{cite web\n |url= https://www.polygon.com/2018/4/25/17280592/captain-america-ships-stucky-stony-steggy\n |title= Captain America is best when he\u2019s shipped\n |last= Downey\n |first= Meg\n |date= 25 April 2018\n |work= [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]\n |publisher= [[Vox Media]]\n |access-date= 29 October 2019\n }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"POLY2\">{{cite web |last1=Alexander |first1=Julie |title=Stucky, Tumblr\u2019s favorite Avengers pairing, only grows stronger after latest tease |url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/4/9/17216408/stucky-captain-america-bucky-avengers-infinity-war-tumblr |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |accessdate=8 November 2019 |date=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"SR\">{{cite web |last1=Steele |first1=Amanda |title=10 Times Stucky Was Canon |url=https://screenrant.com/mcu-steve-bucky-stucky-canon/ |website=[[Screen Rant]] |accessdate=7 November 2019 |date=15 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"THR\">{{cite web |last1=McMillan |first1=Graeme |title=Making Sense of Captain America's Boyfriend, Jane Bond and Fans Online Demands |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/captain-americas-boyfriend-jane-bond-897091 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=7 November 2019 |date=24 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"TIME\">{{cite web |last1=Locker |first1=Melissa |title=Twitter Really Wants Captain America and Bucky Barnes to Be a Couple |url=https://time.com/4346498/captain-america-bucky-barnes-boyfriend/ |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate=8 November 2019 |date=24 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=TRASH>{{cite journal |last1=R\u00edos |first1=Alen |last2=Rivera |first2=Diego |title=Vulnerability and Trash: Divisions within the Stucky Fandom |journal=Otherness: Essays and Studies |date=December 2018 |volume=6 |issue=1 |page=16 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Alen_Rios/publication/330703583_Vulnerability_and_Trash_Divisions_within_the_Stucky_fandom/links/5c503544458515a4c748094f/Vulnerability-and-Trash-Divisions-within-the-Stucky-fandom.pdf |accessdate=6 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"VF1\">{{cite web |last1=Robinson |first1=Joanna |title=Avengers: Why Was This Crucial Friendship Sidelined in Endgame? |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/04/avengers-endgame-steve-bucky-stucky-captain-america-shield-sam-wilson-falcon |website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |accessdate=7 November 2019 |date=26 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"VF2\">{{cite web |last1=Robinson |first1=Joanna |title=Is This the One Flaw in the Otherwise Great Captain America: Civil War? |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/05/captain-america-civil-war-steve-rogers-sharon-carter-bucky-barnes |website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |accessdate=7 November 2019 |date=9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=WAID>{{cite web\n |url= https://www.marvel.com/articles/comics/black-widow-star-crossed\n |title= Black Widow: Star-Crossed\n |last= Cooke\n |first= Sarah\n |date= 28 November 2016\n |work= [[Marvel Comics]]\n |access-date= 28 October 2019\n }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"WAPO\">{{cite web |last1=Guarino |first1=Ben |title=Some fans want Captain America to have a boyfriend, though it won\u2019t be easy to rethink this superhero |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2016/05/25/some-fans-want-captain-america-to-have-a-boyfriend-though-it-wont-be-easy-to-rethink-this-superhero/ |website=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=8 November 2019 |date=25 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Wrap\">{{cite web |last1=Otterson |first1=Joe |title=A Gay Captain America? Marvel Fans Debate Hashtag Demanding Boyfriend for First Avenger |url=https://www.thewrap.com/captain-america-boyfriend-marvel-twitter-hashtag-bucky-barnes-disney-chris-evans/ |website=[[TheWrap]] |accessdate=8 November 2019 |date=24 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n;Bibliography\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Coker |first1=Catherine |title=The creation and evolution of the Avengers and Captain America/Iron Man fandom |journal=[[Transformative Works and Cultures]] |date=2013 |volume=13 |url=https://journal.transformativeworks.org/index.php/twc/article/view/439 |ref=harv|doi=10.3983/twc.2013.0439|doi-access=free}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Coppa |first1=Francesca |editor1-last=Harrod |editor1-first=Mary |editor2-last=Paszkiewicz |editor2-first=Katarzyna |chapter=A Hollywood of Our Own: Media Fandom as Female Artworld |title=Women Do Genre in Film and Television |date=2017 |pages=213\u2013232 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |ref=harv|isbn=9781138695801}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Gillen |first1=Shawn |editor1-last=Weiner |editor1-first=Robert |chapter=Captain America, Post-Traumatic Stress Syndrome, and the Vietnam Era |title=Captain America and the Struggle of the Superhero: Critical Essays |date=2009 |pages=104\u2013115 |publisher=[[McFarland & Company]] |ref=harv|isbn=978-0786437030}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Stevens |first1=J Richard |title=Captain America, Masculinity, and Violence: The Evolution of a National Icon |date=2015 |publisher=[[Syracuse University Press]] |isbn=978-0815633952 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite thesis|first1=Jingyi|last1= Gu|url=https://repository.library.georgetown.edu/bitstream/handle/10822/1043829/Gu_georgetown_0076M_13731.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y |title=Celebrating and Discussing the Queerly Masculine: Hollywood Superheroes Reimagined in Fan Videos on Chinese Barrage Video Websites| publisher=Georgetown University |date=2017}} Research on an expression of the Stucky fandom in China.\n\n{{Captain America}}\n{{Fan fiction}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stucky}}\n[[Category:Captain America]]\n[[Category:Slash fiction]]\n[[Category:Fandom]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n[[File:Gwenpool Stucky Panel.png|thumb|upright=2|right|An exchange from ''[[Gwenpool|Gwenpool Strikes Back]]'' #3 (2019) interpreted by commentators as a humorous acknowledgement of the Stucky fandom by Marvel.<ref name=\"GWENPOOL\"/>|alt=Comic panel from \"Gwenpool Strikes Back\" #3 featuring Steve Rogers and Bucky Barnes.]]\n\n'''Stucky''', also '''Steve/Bucky''' or '''Bucky/Steve''',{{efn|The ship names '''Wintershield''', '''Starbucks''', and '''Barnes & Noble''' are also occasionally used.<ref name=\"MarySue1\"/>}} is the [[Shipping (fandom)|ship name]] given to the [[Slash fiction|slash]] pairing of [[Captain America|Steve Rogers]] ([[Captain America]]) and [[Bucky Barnes]] (the [[Bucky Barnes|Winter Soldier]]),{{efn|Per [[Shipping (fandom)#Naming conventions|shipping naming conventions]], Stucky is a [[portmanteau]] of \"Steve\" and \"Bucky\".<ref name=\"TRASH\"/>}} fictional characters appearing in [[American comic book|comic books]] and related media produced by [[Marvel Comics]]. Though Rogers and Barnes have appeared in media dating to the 1940s, [[Fan labor|fan works]] depicting a romantic or sexual relationship between the characters grew substantially in popularity in the 2010s following their appearances in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] (MCU). Several individuals associated with Marvel, including Winter Soldier co-creator [[Ed Brubaker]], Barnes' actor [[Sebastian Stan]], and MCU director [[Russo brothers|Joe Russo]], have commented positively on Stucky. Critics and commentators have used the popularity of Stucky in [[fandom]] to remark on a range of topics, including the lack of [[LGBT]] characters in [[superhero films]] and the nature of fandom on social media.\n\n==Background==\n===Marvel Comics===\n[[Captain America|Steve Rogers]] and [[Bucky Barnes]] first appeared in ''[[Captain America#Golden Age|Captain America Comics]]'' #1 (March 1941), which establishes Rogers as Captain America and Barnes as his teenaged [[sidekick]]. Barnes would be killed in 1948 and would not re-appear until [[Captain America (vol. 5)|''Captain America'' (vol. 5)]] in 2005, where the character is [[comic book death|brought back from supposed death]] as the Winter Soldier, a brainwashed assassin.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hall |first1=Richard |title=The American Superhero: Encyclopedia of Caped Crusaders in History |publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]] |location=Santa Barbara, California |isbn=978-1440861239 |page=102}}</ref> As a result of Barnes' extended absence from comics, and Rogers' initial characterization as a much older [[paternal]] figure to Barnes, the emergence of Stucky as a phenomenon in [[fandom]] is a relatively recent development;<ref name=\"POLY1\"/> in pre-social media [[Shipping (fandom)|shipping]] fandom of the early 2000s, Rogers was most commonly depicted with [[Tony Stark]] ([[Iron Man]]), the pairing typically abbreviated as \"Stony\" or \"Superhusbands\".<ref name=\"POLY1\"/>{{sfn|Coker|2013|pp=1.8}}\n\nWhile hero-and-sidekick relationships in comics are frequently interpreted as having a [[homoerotic]] subtext \u2014 an argument infamously made by [[Fredric Wertham]] in his 1954 book ''[[Seduction of the Innocent]]'', which asserted that [[Batman]] and [[Robin (character)|Robin]]'s relationship promotes homosexuality and pederasty \u2014 in Marvel [[Canon (fiction)|canon]], the relationship between Rogers and Barnes is strictly platonic, and is not depicted as sexual or romantic.{{sfn|Gillen|2009|pp=109}} Regardless, Rogers and Barnes are consistently depicted in-canon as having a deep and meaningful personal bond, with some critics likening their relationship as wartime compatriots to [[Achilles and Patroclus]].{{sfn|Gillen|2009|pp=109}}\n\n===Marvel Cinematic Universe===\n{{See also|Steve Rogers (Marvel Cinematic Universe)}}\n{{multiple image\n | width1 = 120\n | image1 = Chris Evans - Captain America 2 press conference (cropped2).jpg\n | alt1 = Actor Chris Evans at a press conference in 2014.\n | image2 = Sebastian Stan by Gage Skidmore 2 (cropped).jpg\n | width2 = 120\n | alt2 = Actor Sebastian Stan at San Diego Comic-Con International in 2019.\n | footer = Actors [[Chris Evans (actor)|Chris Evans]] (left) and [[Sebastian Stan]] (right), who portray Steve Rogers and Bucky Barnes, respectively, in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] (MCU).\n}}\n\nThe popularity of Stucky as a ship in fandom rose substantially following the introduction of Rogers and Barnes to the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] (MCU),<ref name=\"POLY1\"/> where they have jointly appeared in five films: ''[[Captain America: The First Avenger]]'' (2011), ''[[Captain America: The Winter Soldier]]'' (2014), ''[[Captain America: Civil War]]'' (2016), ''[[Avengers: Infinity War]]'' (2018), and ''[[Avengers: Endgame]]'' (2019). The films re-conceptualize the nature of Rogers' and Barnes' relationship, presenting them as same-age lifelong best friends,<ref name=\"POLY1\"/>{{sfn|Coker|2013|pp=1.7}} and establish their bond as a key plot element and mutual character motivation.<ref name=\"DOT\"/><ref name=\"POLY2\"/> As a result, a fandom developed in reaction to a supposed homoerotic subtext to Rogers' and Barnes' relationship.<ref name=\"VF1\"/><ref name=\"MTV\"/>\n\nAcross the ''Captain America'' trilogy of films, Gavia Baker-Whitelaw of ''[[The Daily Dot]]'' notes that Rogers continually \"rebel[s] against authority for the sake of Bucky's wellbeing, escalating from disobeying orders in [[World War II]], to becoming an international fugitive in ''Civil War''.\"<ref name=\"DOT\"/> The relationship serves as the driving plot to ''The Winter Soldier'', where Barnes' memory of Rogers causes him to overcome his conditioning as a brainwashed assassin;<ref name=\"MTV\"/> Barnes recalls his identity through Rogers' declaration of \"I'm with you till the end of the line\", a phrase repeated by Rogers and Barnes throughout the series as an expression of kinship.<ref name=\"SR\"/> Their relationship is again a central plot element in ''Civil War'', as Rogers protects Barnes after he is wrongly accused of committing a terrorist act.<ref name=\"BEAST\"/> That film also develops [[Sharon Carter]] as a love interest for Rogers; writing for ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', Joanna Robinson called the development the \"one flaw in the otherwise great\" film, arguing that the film's kiss between Rogers and Carter exists primarily to \"put the nail in the coffin of speculation\" around a homoerotic interpretation of Rogers' and Barnes' relationship.<ref name=\"VF2\"/> While Rogers and Barnes appear in both ''Infinity War'' and ''Endgame'', comparably less time is spent on developing their relationship,<ref name=\"BUSTLE\"/><ref name=\"CB1\"/> with Robinson and other critics hypothesizing that their interactions were minimized to build popularity for [[Falcon (comics)|Sam Wilson]] ([[Falcon (comics)|Falcon]]) as he assumes the mantle of Captain America, and to emphasize the canonical love story between Rogers and [[Peggy Carter]].<ref name=\"VF1\"/><ref name=\"DOG\"/><ref name=\"BEAT\"/>\n\n==Analysis and impact==\nStucky as a phenomenon in [[fandom]] emerged from online communities that produce [[Fan labor|fan works]]. These online communities are typically majority female, in contrast to the majority male mainstream comics fandom.{{sfn|Coker|2013|pp=1.1}} Fan works featuring Stucky cover a wide range of mediums, including [[fan art]], [[fanfiction]], and [[Vidding|fan videos]], and typically give prominence to emotional imagery and romantic subject material, as opposed to the action- and conflict-centered narratives of Marvel's comic and film source material.{{sfn|Coker|2013|pp=1.1}}{{sfn|Coppa|2017|pp=220}} Stucky fan works thus \"realize all the un-filmed narrative moments that fans want to see,\"{{sfn|Coppa|2017|pp=226}} with depictions of Rogers' and Barnes' domestic life in 1940s New York \u2013 largely unexplored in canonical source material \u2013 being a common trope in Stucky fan works.<ref name=\"MARYSUE\"/> In lieu of canonical material than can be drawn from, these particular works often maintain a high degree of historical fidelity; ''Gay New York'', a sociological text by LGBT historian [[George Chauncey]], is noted as having been utilized by some fan creators to accurately depict aspects of [[LGBT history in New York#1900\u20131949|pre-war gay culture in New York City]], including real-life period-specific [[gay bar]]s that existed in Rogers' canonical Brooklyn neighborhood.<ref name=\"MARYSUE\"/>{{sfn|Coppa|2017|pp=224}}\n\nIn ''Captain America, Masculinity, and Violence: The Evolution of a National Icon'', author J. Richard Stevens argues that fans of Captain America use the character \"to reconstruct and reconfigure cultural significance in their own lives,\"{{sfn|Stevens|2015|pp=10}} noting that \"throughout the character's history, which contains messages from ultranationalist [[jingoism]] to a critique of the role of [[nationalism]] in the propagation of racism and terrorism, his narratives have provoked incredibly articulate responses.\"{{sfn|Stevens|2015|pp=2}} In the specific case of Stucky, Francesca Coppa argues that the fandom is a response to the unlikelihood of Marvel acknowledging a queer reading of Rogers' and Barnes' relationship in canon, and a desire by some fans to formulate what such an acknowledgement could look like.{{sfn|Coppa|2017|pp=226}} Thus, Stucky represents both the [[objectification]] and [[Subjectification (linguistics)|subjectification]] of Steve Rogers as character, \"with fans writing stories that flesh out his politics, his relationships past and present, his religion, and his sexuality.\"{{sfn|Coppa|2017|pp=223}} In this regard, Stucky as a phenomenon in [[Shipping (fandom)|shipping]] is notable in that it devotes significant focus to the characters' imagined homosexuality or bisexuality,{{sfn|Coppa|2017|pp=224}} in contrast to [[Slash fiction|slash fan works]] of the 1970s and 1980s that \"distanc[ed] beloved characters from the stereotypes and even the identity of gayness,\" opting to instead depict the characters as \"sharing a great, transcendent love that eliminated the boundaries of gender.\"{{sfn|Coker|2013|pp=1.9}}\n\nThe popularity of Stucky in fandom has been widely commented on by mainstream pop culture and entertainment sources.<ref name=\"SR\"/><ref name=\"MARYSUE\"/>{{sfn|Coppa|2017|pp=225}} In [[Tumblr]]'s annual rankings of the most popular ships of the year (as measured by number of [[Reblogging|reblogs]]), Stucky placed 17th in 2014,<ref>{{cite web |title=Most Reblogged Ships |url=https://2014inreblogs.tumblr.com/post/133384976809/most-reblogged-ships-ship-noun-short-for |website=2014 Tumblr Year in Review |publisher=[[Tumblr]] |accessdate=29 October 2019 |date=17 November 2014}}</ref> 9th in 2015,<ref>{{cite web |title=Most Reblogged Ships |url=https://yearinreview.tumblr.com/post/134751774307/most-reblogged-ships |website=Tumblr 2015 Year in Review |publisher=[[Tumblr]] |accessdate=29 October 2019 |date=7 December 2015}}</ref> 8th in 2016,<ref>{{cite web |title=2016\u2019s Top Ships |url=https://fandom.tumblr.com/post/153998280734/ships |website=Fandom on Tumblr |publisher=[[Tumblr]] |accessdate=29 October 2019 |date=3 December 2016}}</ref> 10th in 2018,<ref>{{cite web |title=2018\u2019s Top Ships |url=https://fandom.tumblr.com/post/180587157919/2018-ships |website=Fandom on Tumblr |publisher=[[Tumblr]] |accessdate=29 October 2019 |date=28 November 2018}}</ref> and 16th in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=2019\u2019s Top 100 Ships |url=https://fandom.tumblr.com/post/189431747929/2019-ships |website=Fandom on Tumblr |publisher=[[Tumblr]] |accessdate=7 December 2019 |date=2 December 2019}}</ref> Over 45,000 Stucky fan works have been published on [[Archive of Our Own]], making Stucky among the most popular ships on the website.<ref>{{cite web |title=James \"Bucky\" Barnes/Steve Rogers |url=https://archiveofourown.org/tags/James%20%22Bucky%22%20Barnes*s*Steve%20Rogers/works |website=[[Archive of Our Own]] |accessdate=26 November 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191123011829/https://archiveofourown.org/tags/James%20%22Bucky%22%20Barnes*s*Steve%20Rogers/works |archivedate=23 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===#GiveCaptainAmericaABoyfriend===\nIn May 2016, [[Twitter]] user Jess Salerno tweeted \"#givecaptainamericaaboyfriend\" in response to a similar [[Internet activism|internet campaign]] around the [[hashtag]] #GiveElsaAGirlfriend, which focused on [[Elsa (Frozen)|Elsa]] from the 2013 film ''[[Frozen (2013 film)|Frozen]]''.<ref name=\"MetroUK\"/><ref name=\"Kotaku1\"/> The hashtag became a viral [[Twitter trends|trending topic]] on Twitter,<ref name=\"Wrap\"/> and was widely covered by the mainstream press.<ref name=\"MetroUK\"/><ref name=\"EW\"/><ref name=\"AP\"/><ref name=\"WAPO\"/><ref name=\"TIME\"/> While the hashtag was ostensibly organized around fans who wished to see Stucky made canon, both it and #GiveElsaAGirlfriend were also broadly concerned with the lack of LGBT characters in media properties owned by [[Disney]], of which Marvel is a subsidiary.<ref name=\"Crush\"/><ref name=\"IO9\"/> The LGBT rights organization [[GLAAD]] commented that the hashtag was \"a sign that audiences are eager for significant LGBT characters in their superhero movies.\"<ref name=\"AP\"/>\n\n''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' cited #GiveCaptainAmericaABoyfriend as an example of how social media has altered the dynamic between creators and audiences, as the medium increases both the visibility of fan discussions and the willingness of creators to respond to these discussions.<ref name=\"THR\"/> In the specific case of #GiveCaptainAmericaABoyfriend, ''The Hollywood Reporter'' noted that the campaign \"highlights demographic shifts that have yet to be reflected in the texts audiences are responding to,\" in reference to the popularity of Stucky relative to the lack of LGBT characters in superhero films.<ref name=\"THR\"/>\n\n==Response==\n{{Rquote |1=right |2= What\u2019s fascinating about the Cap-Bucky story as well is it\u2019s a love story. These are two guys who grew up together, and so they have that same emotional connection to each other as brothers would, and even more so because Bucky was all Steve had growing up. |3=[[Russo brothers|Joe Russo]] |4=<br>Marvel Cinematic Universe director<ref name=\"EMPIRE\"/>}}\n\nSeveral individuals affiliated with Marvel have commented on Stucky, frequently in a context that affirms Rogers' and Barnes' canonical heterosexuality while offering support for the broader Stucky fandom.\n\nRogers' actor [[Chris Evans (actor)|Chris Evans]] has commented positively on romantic interpretations on Rogers' relationship with Barnes, though qualified that \"it's just never been part of my approach to the character.\"<ref name=\"POLY2\"/><ref name=\"MYTH\"/> When asked about Stucky in a separate interview interview with ''[[GQ]]'', Barnes' actor [[Sebastian Stan]] similarly responded that \"I think it's great. Movies are for people to relate to in whatever way they want,\" adding that \"I don't think of the character that way, though. But there's no right or wrong answer.\"<ref name=\"GQ\"/> Evans has separately remarked that Barnes is \"one of the more precious relationships for Steve Rogers [...] it's one of the few relationships that he can identify as anything we would call home,\"<ref name=\"MOVIEFONE\"/> which has been quoted by outlets in the context of their coverage of Stucky.<ref name=\"VF1\"/><ref name=\"MOVIEFONE\"/><ref name=\"BUZZFEED1\"/> An image from a fan [[photo op]] of Evans and Stan at [[Wizard World Philadelphia]] posing with [[cosplay]]ers kissing while dressed as Rogers and Barnes went viral in 2016.<ref name=\"IO9\"/><ref name=\"OW\"/>\n\n[[Russo brothers|Joe Russo]], who co-directed four of the five MCU films in which Rogers and Barnes jointly appear, has described their relationship as a love story,<ref name=\"EMPIRE\"/> later stating that \"people have interpreted that relationship all kinds of ways, and it's great to see people argue about it what that relationship means to them. We will never define it as filmmakers, explicitly, but however people want to interpret it, they can interpret it.\"<ref name=\"VF1\"/><ref name=\"MTV\"/> Screenwriters [[Christopher Markus and Stephen McFeely]], who jointly wrote the ''Captain America'' film trilogy, ''Infinity War'', and ''Endgame'', likened Rogers and Barnes' relationship to a love story and described the characters as soulmates in the foreword of the [[Trade paperback (comics)|trade paperback]] edition of the comic book series ''[[Captain America: White]]''.<ref name=HCForeward>{{cite book|contributor-last1=Markus|contributor-first1=Christopher|contributor-last2=McFeely|contributor-first2=Stephen|contribution=Introduction |date=2016|title=Captain America: White|last1=Loeb|first1=Jeph | publisher=Marvel Comics|isbn=978-0785133766|ref=harv|pages=1\u20132}}</ref>\n\nOther individuals who have remarked positively on Stucky include writers [[Ed Brubaker]], who co-created the Winter Soldier with artist [[Steve Epting]],<ref name=\"BC\"/> and [[Mark Waid]], who remarked in an interview with Marvel regarding his 2016 run on the comic book series ''[[Black Widow (Marvel Comics)|Black Widow]]'' that both Black Widow and Barnes \"have had a crush\" on Steve Rogers.<ref name=\"WAID\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kirk/Spock]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite web |last1=Bahr |first1=Lindsey |title=GLAAD responds to #GiveCaptainAmericaABoyfriend |url=http://apnews.com/8957b80de9f444b7bc7f91ecc8184cb7 |website=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=8 November 2019 |date=25 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BEAST\">{{cite web |last1=Yamato |first1=Jen |title=\u2018Captain America: Civil War\u2019 Star Sebastian Stan on Whether Bucky and Cap Are in Love |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/captain-america-civil-war-star-sebastian-stan-on-whether-bucky-and-cap-are-in-love |website=[[The Daily Beast]] |accessdate=7 November 2019 |date=9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BEAT\">{{cite web |last1=Steele |first1=Amanda |title=Queer Coding Bucky Barnes: Why the MCU Should Put Up |url=https://www.comicsbeat.com/bucky-barnes-queer-coding/ |website=[[Comics Beat]] |accessdate=8 November 2019 |date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=BC>{{cite web\n |url= https://www.bleedingcool.com/2016/05/27/ed-brubaker-talks-captain-america/\n |title= Ed Brubaker Talks Captain America. Or Not.\n |last= Johnson\n |first= Rich\n |date= 27 May 2016\n |work= [[Bleeding Cool]]\n |access-date= 28 October 2019\n }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BUSTLE\">{{cite web |last1=Florio |first1=Angelica |title=The Lack Of Stucky Moments In \u2018Endgame\u2019 Has Steve & Bucky Shippers In Their Feelings |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/the-lack-of-stucky-moments-in-endgame-has-steve-bucky-shippers-in-their-feelings-17227283 |website=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |accessdate=7 November 2019 |date=26 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BUZZFEED1\">{{cite web |last1=Wieselman |first1=Jarett |title=Chris Evans Has A Theory Why Fans Love His Rel