{"title_page": "Whitby Mudstone", "text_new": "{{Infobox rockunit\n| name           = Whitby Mudstone\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| type           = [[Geological formation]]\n| age            = [[Toarcian]] ([[Falciferum]]-[[Bifrons (age)|Bifrons]])<br>~{{fossilrange|183|176}}\n| period         = Toarcian\n| prilithology   = [[Mudstone]]\n| otherlithology = [[Siltstone]]\n| namedfor       = [[Whitby]]\n| namedby        = \n| region         = [[Yorkshire]], [[Worcestershire]]\n| country        = {{ENG}}\n| coordinates    = {{coord|54.5|N|0.6|W|display=title,inline}} \n| paleocoordinates = {{coord|42.5|N|9.3|E|display=inline}}\n| unitof         = [[Lias Group]]\n| subunits       = Members:<br>\n* Fox Cliff Siltstone\n* Peak Mudstone\n* Alum Shale{{refn|group=note|Not to be confused with the Ordovician [[Alum Shale]] [[Lagerst\u00e4tte]] of Sweden}}\n* Mulgrave Shale\n* Grey Shale\n| underlies      = [[Inferior Oolite Group|Inferior Oolite]] or [[Ravenscar Group]]s<br>Or [[Blea Wyke Formation|Blea Wyke]], [[Dogger Formation|Dogger]] or [[Bridport Sand Formation]]s\n| overlies       = [[Marlstone Rock Formation|Marlstone Rock]] or [[Cleveland Ironstone Formation]]s\n| thickness      = Up to {{convert|120|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| extent         = [[Cleveland Basin|Cleveland]] & [[Worcester Basin]]s & [[East Midlands Shelf]]\n| area           =\n| map            = {{Location map+ | United Kingdom#England\n| relief = 1\n| width   = 250\n| float   = center\n| places  =\n  {{Location map~ | United Kingdom#England\n  | lat_deg = 54.5\n  | lon_deg = -0.6\n  | mark = Blue pog.svg\n  | marksize = 8\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | United Kingdom#England\n  | lat_deg = 54.5\n  | lon_deg = -0.7\n  | mark = Blue pog.svg\n  | marksize = 8\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | United Kingdom#England\n  | lat_deg = 54.4\n  | lon_deg = -0.6\n  | mark = Blue pog.svg\n  | marksize = 8\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | United Kingdom#England\n  | lat_deg = 52.3\n  | lon_deg = -0.9\n  | mark = Blue pog.svg\n  | marksize = 8\n  }}\n}}\n| map_caption    =\n}}\nThe '''Whitby Mudstone''' is a [[Toarcian]] ([[Early Jurassic]]; [[Falciferum]]-[[Bifrons (age)|Bifrons]] in regional chronostratigraphy) geological [[Formation (geology)|formation]] in [[Yorkshire]] and [[Worcestershire]], [[England]].<ref name=FWWhitby>[http://fossilworks.org/bridge.pl?action=displayStrata&geological_group=&formation=Whitby%20Mudstone&group_formation_member=Whitby%20Mudstone Whitby Mudstone] at [[Fossilworks]].org</ref> The formation, part of the [[Lias Group]], is present in the [[Cleveland Basin|Cleveland]] and [[Worcester Basin]]s and the [[East Midlands Shelf]].\n\n== Fossil content ==\n[[Dinosaur]] remains are among the fossils that have been recovered from the formation, although none have yet been referred to a specific [[genus]].<ref name=\"BGS lexicon\">{{cite web | url=http://www.bgs.ac.uk/lexicon/lexicon.cfm?pub=WHM | title=Whitby Mudstone Formation | publisher=[[British Geological Survey]] | work=The BGS lexicon of named rock units | accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"dinosaurdistribution\">Weishampel et al., 2004, pp. 517-607</ref>. One of the more notable discoveries is the skull of the pterosaur ''[[Parapsicephalus]]'', found within the Alum Shale{{refn|group=note|Not to be confused with the Ordovician [[Alum Shale]] [[Lagerst\u00e4tte]] of Sweden}} Member.<ref name=Martill2017>O'Sullivan & Martill, 2017</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of fossiliferous stratigraphic units in England]]\n* [[Toarcian turnover]]\n* [[:Category:Toarcian Stage|Toarcian formations]]\n**[[Marne di Monte Serrone]], Italy\n** [[Calcare di Sogno]], Italy\n** [[Sachrang Formation]], Austria\n** [[Posidonia Shale]], [[Lagerst\u00e4tte]] in Germany\n** [[Ciechocinek Formation]], Germany and Poland\n** [[Krempachy Marl Formation]], Poland and Slovakia\n** [[Lava Formation]], Lithuania\n** [[Azilal Group]], North Africa\n** [[Junction Bed]], Toarcian fossiliferous unit of the Lias Group\n** [[Fernie Formation]], Alberta and British Columbia\n*** [[Poker Chip Shale]]\n** [[Whiteaves Formation]], British Columbia\n** [[Navajo Sandstone]], Utah\n** [[Los Molles Formation]], Argentina\n** [[Mawson Formation]], Antarctica\n** [[Kandreho Formation]], Madagascar\n** [[Kota Formation]], India\n** [[Cattamarra Coal Measures]], Australia\n\n== Notes and references ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n=== References ===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite LSA |last=O'Sullivan |first=Michael |last2=Martill |first2=David M. |year=2017 |title=The taxonomy and systematics of Parapsicephalus purdoni (Reptilia: Pterosauria) from the Lower Jurassic Whitby Mudstone Formation, Whitby, U.K |url=https://researchportal.port.ac.uk/portal/files/8204570/The_taxonomy_and_systematics.pdf |journal=[[Historical Biology]] |volume=29 |pages=1009\u20131018 |accessdate=2020-03-12}} {{doi|10.1080/08912963.2017.1281919}}\n* {{cite LSA |last=[[David B. Weishampel|Weishampel]] |first=David B. |last2=[[Peter Dodson|Dodson]] |first2=Peter |last3=[[Halszka Osm\u00f3lska|Osm\u00f3lska]] (eds.) |first3=Halszka |year=2004 |title=The Dinosauria, 2nd edition |url=https://books.google.com.co/books/about/The_Dinosauria.html?id=vtZFDb_iw40C&redir_esc=y |publisher=Berkeley: University of California Press |pages=1\u2013880 |accessdate=2019-02-21}}{{ISBN|0-520-24209-2}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* M. O'Sullivan, D. M. Martill, and D. Groocock. 2013. A pterosaur humerus and scapulocoracoid from the Jurassic Whitby Mudstone Formation, and the evolution of large body size in early pterosaurs. Proceedings of the Geologists' Association\n* A. S. Smith and G. J. Dyke. 2008. The skull of the giant predatory pliosaur ''Rhomaleosaurus cramptoni'': implications for plesiosaur phylogenetics. Naturwissenschaften 95:975-980 \n* M. J. Benton and M. A. Taylor. 1984. Marine reptiles from the Upper Lias (Lower Toarcian, Lower Jurassic) of the Yorkshire coast. Proceedings of the Yorkshire Geological Society 44(4):399-429\n* F. v. Huene. 1926. The carnivorous Saurischia in the Jura and Cretaceous formations, principally in Europe. Revista del Museo de La Plata 29:35-167\n* C. W. Andrews. 1922. Note on the skeleton of a large plesiosaur (''Rhomaleosaurus thorntoni'', sp. n) from the Upper Lias of Northamptonshire. Annals and Magazine of Natural History 10:407-415\n* R. Tate and J. F. Blake. 1876. The Yorkshire Lias 1-475\n\n[[Category:Geologic formations of England]]\n[[Category:Jurassic England]]\n[[Category:Early Jurassic Europe]]\n[[Category:Toarcian Stage]]\n[[Category:Mudstone formations]]\n[[Category:Shallow marine deposits]]\n[[Category:Open marine deposits]]\n[[Category:Paleontology in England]]\n[[Category:Geography of Yorkshire|Formations]]\n[[Category:Geography of Worcestershire|Formations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rockunit\n| name           = Whitby Mudstone\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| type           = [[Geological formation]]\n| age            = [[Toarcian]] ([[Falciferum]]-[[Bifrons (age)|Bifrons]])<br>~{{fossilrange|183|176}}\n| period         = Toarcian\n| prilithology   = [[Mudstone]]\n| otherlithology = [[Siltstone]]\n| namedfor       = [[Whitby]]\n| namedby        = \n| region         = [[Yorkshire]], [[Worcestershire]]\n| country        = {{ENG}}\n| coordinates    = {{coord|54.5|N|0.6|W|display=title,inline}} \n| paleocoordinates = {{coord|42.5|N|9.3|E|display=inline}}\n| unitof         = [[Lias Group]]\n| subunits       = Members:<br>\n* Fox Cliff Siltstone\n* Peak Mudstone\n* Alum Shale{{refn|group=note|Not to be confused with the Ordovician [[Alum Shale]] [[Lagerst\u00e4tte]] of Sweden}}\n* Mulgrave Shale\n* Grey Shale\n| underlies      = [[Inferior Oolite Group|Inferior Oolite]] or [[Ravenscar Group]]s<br>Or [[Blea Wyke Formation|Blea Wyke]], [[Dogger Formation|Dogger]] or [[Bridport Sand Formation]]s\n| overlies       = [[Marlstone Rock Formation|Marlstone Rock]] or [[Cleveland Ironstone Formation]]s\n| thickness      = Up to {{convert|120|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| extent         = [[Cleveland Basin|Cleveland]] & [[Worcester Basin]]s & [[East Midlands Shelf]]\n| area           =\n| map            = {{Location map+ | United Kingdom#England\n| relief = 1\n| width   = 250\n| float   = center\n| places  =\n  {{Location map~ | United Kingdom#England\n  | lat_deg = 54.5\n  | lon_deg = -0.6\n  | mark = Blue pog.svg\n  | marksize = 8\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | United Kingdom#England\n  | lat_deg = 54.5\n  | lon_deg = -0.7\n  | mark = Blue pog.svg\n  | marksize = 8\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | United Kingdom#England\n  | lat_deg = 54.4\n  | lon_deg = -0.6\n  | mark = Blue pog.svg\n  | marksize = 8\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | United Kingdom#England\n  | lat_deg = 52.3\n  | lon_deg = -0.9\n  | mark = Blue pog.svg\n  | marksize = 8\n  }}\n}}\n| map_caption    =\n}}\nThe '''Whitby Mudstone''' is a [[Toarcian]] ([[Early Jurassic]]; [[Falciferum]]-[[Bifrons (age)|Bifrons]] in regional chronostratigraphy) geological [[Formation (geology)|formation]] in [[Yorkshire]] and [[Worcestershire]], [[England]].<ref name=FWWhitby>[http://fossilworks.org/bridge.pl?action=displayStrata&geological_group=&formation=Whitby%20Mudstone&group_formation_member=Whitby%20Mudstone Whitby Mudstone] at [[Fossilworks]].org</ref> The formation, part of the [[Lias Group]], is present in the [[Cleveland Basin|Cleveland]] and [[Worcester Basin]]s and the [[East Midlands Shelf]].\n\n== Fossil content ==\n[[Dinosaur]] remains are among the fossils that have been recovered from the formation, although none have yet been referred to a specific [[genus]].<ref name=\"BGS lexicon\">{{cite web | url=http://www.bgs.ac.uk/lexicon/lexicon.cfm?pub=WHM | title=Whitby Mudstone Formation | publisher=[[British Geological Survey]] | work=The BGS lexicon of named rock units | accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"dinosaurdistribution\">Weishampel et al., 2004, pp. 517-607</ref>. One of the more notable discoveries is the skull of the pterosaur ''[[Parapsicephalus]]'', found within the Alum Shale{{refn|group=note|Not to be confused with the Ordovician [[Alum Shale]] [[Lagerst\u00e4tte]] of Sweden}} Member.<ref name=Martill2017>O'Sullivan & Martill, 2017</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of fossiliferous stratigraphic units in Italy]]\n* [[Toarcian turnover]]\n* [[:Category:Toarcian Stage|Toarcian formations]]\n**[[Marne di Monte Serrone]], Italy\n** [[Calcare di Sogno]], Italy\n** [[Sachrang Formation]], Austria\n** [[Posidonia Shale]], [[Lagerst\u00e4tte]] in Germany\n** [[Ciechocinek Formation]], Germany and Poland\n** [[Krempachy Marl Formation]], Poland and Slovakia\n** [[Lava Formation]], Lithuania\n** [[Azilal Group]], North Africa\n** [[Junction Bed]], Toarcian fossiliferous unit of the Lias Group\n** [[Fernie Formation]], Alberta and British Columbia\n*** [[Poker Chip Shale]]\n** [[Whiteaves Formation]], British Columbia\n** [[Navajo Sandstone]], Utah\n** [[Los Molles Formation]], Argentina\n** [[Mawson Formation]], Antarctica\n** [[Kandreho Formation]], Madagascar\n** [[Kota Formation]], India\n** [[Cattamarra Coal Measures]], Australia\n\n== Notes and references ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n=== References ===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite LSA |last=O'Sullivan |first=Michael |last2=Martill |first2=David M. |year=2017 |title=The taxonomy and systematics of Parapsicephalus purdoni (Reptilia: Pterosauria) from the Lower Jurassic Whitby Mudstone Formation, Whitby, U.K |url=https://researchportal.port.ac.uk/portal/files/8204570/The_taxonomy_and_systematics.pdf |journal=[[Historical Biology]] |volume=29 |pages=1009\u20131018 |accessdate=2020-03-12}} {{doi|10.1080/08912963.2017.1281919}}\n* {{cite LSA |last=[[David B. Weishampel|Weishampel]] |first=David B. |last2=[[Peter Dodson|Dodson]] |first2=Peter |last3=[[Halszka Osm\u00f3lska|Osm\u00f3lska]] (eds.) |first3=Halszka |year=2004 |title=The Dinosauria, 2nd edition |url=https://books.google.com.co/books/about/The_Dinosauria