{"title_page": "Nigel Pepper", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Nigel Pepper\n| image = \n| fullname = Colin Nigel Pepper\n| height = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1968|4|25}}\n| birth_place = [[Rotherham]], England\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1986\u20131990 \n| years2 = 1990\u20131997 \n| years3 = 1997\u20131998 \n| years4 = 1998\u20132000 \n| years5 = 1999\u20132000 \n| years6 = 2000\u20132002 \n| years7 = 2002\u20132008\n| clubs1 = [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] \n| clubs2 = [[York City F.C.|York City]] \n| clubs3 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] \n| clubs4 = [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] \n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] (loan) \n| clubs6 = [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] \n| clubs7 = [[Barrow A.F.C.|Barrow]]\n| caps1 = 45   \n| caps2 = 235  \n| caps3 = 52  \n| caps4 = 14   \n| caps5 = 12   \n| caps6 = 3   \n| caps7 = ?   \n| goals1 = 1  \n| goals2 = 39  \n| goals3 = 11  \n| goals4 = 0  \n| goals5 = 2  \n| goals6 = 0  \n| goals7 = ?\n}}\n\n'''Colin Nigel Pepper''' (born 25 April 1968 in [[Rotherham]], England), more commonly known as '''Nigel Pepper''', is an English retired professional [[Association football|footballer]]. He was a combative midfield player known for his powerful attacking free kicks and his solid work ethic. He was a member of the [[York City F.C.|York City]] \nteam that beat [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] 3\u20130 at [[Old Trafford (football ground)|Old Trafford]] in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] in 1995.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Rotherham===\nPepper joined his hometown club [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] as an apprentice in 1985 when the club was playing in the old Division 3. He made his debut on 8 May 1986 at [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] aged just 17.<ref>[http://www.themillers.co.uk/staticFiles/87/1b/0,,10360~7047,00.doc Rotherham FC Players Factsheet] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208092603/http://www.themillers.co.uk/staticFiles/87/1b/0%2C%2C10360~7047%2C00.doc |date=8 February 2012 }}</ref> His first goal for the club came in a 3-2 [[Football League Cup|Littlewoods Cup]] defeat at [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].\n\nHis only league goal for the club came in a 4\u20132 home win against [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] on 25 November 1989, when he came on as substitute.\n\nHe remained at the club until 1990 and was a part of the side both relegated in 1988 and promoted in 1989.\n\n===York City===\nFollowing a lack of first team opportunities at Rotherham, Pepper signed for [[York City F.C.|York City]] on a free transfer on 18 July 1990.<ref name=\"sporting-heroes.net\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sporting-heroes.net/football/bradford-city-fc/nigel-pepper-9280/1996-97-1998-99_a17334|title=Sorry, the page was not found|publisher=|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref> He made his debut in the 1990\u201391 season against [[Maidstone United F.C. (1897)|Maidstone United]]. He helped the club secure promotion in 1992-93 scoring one of York's penalties in the [[1993 Football League Third Division play-off Final|1993 Playoff Final]] shootout victory at Wembley over [[Crewe Alexandra|Crewe]]. In that season he also took over as the clubs penalty taker and netted 19 out of 22 penalties between 1990\u20131997. He was also pivotal in York making the Playoff Semi-Finals the following season, although they did not secure promotion, losing 1\u20130 over two legs to [[Stockport County]].\n\nPepper was a member of the York team that beat [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] over two legs in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] in 1995. Having beaten a weakened United team 3\u20130 at [[Old Trafford (football ground)|Old Trafford]], York were beaten 3\u20131 at [[Bootham Crescent]] in the second leg but went through 4\u20133 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-484253/Red-faced-Manchester-Uniteds-cup-shocks-years.html|title=Red-faced: Manchester United's cup shocks over the years|work=Mail Online|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe following season, also in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]], Pepper played in the York side that defeated [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] 4\u20133 over two legs.\n\nHe made 281 league and cup appearances for the club, scoring 45 times.<ref>[http://www.yorkcityfootballclub.co.uk/players/n/nigel-pepper.php York City Profile]</ref> His final game for club came on 25 February 1997 when he scored in a 3\u20131 home win over [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston]].\n\n===Bradford City===\nPepper joined [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] on 28 February 1997 for a fee of \u00a3100,000.<ref name=\"sporting-heroes.net\"/> Bradford manager [[Chris Kamara]] brought him in to add some steel to his central midfield. He made his club debut on 1 March 1997 in a 3\u20131 defeat at home to [[Manchester City]]. He went on to make a total of 52 appearance for Bradford over 3 seasons in Division 1, scoring 11 goals and helping them avoid relegation.\n\n===Aberdeen===\nOn 26 November 1998 Pepper moved to [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] for a fee of \u00a3300,000.<ref name=\"sporting-heroes.net\"/> He did not enjoy the best of starts being sent off on his debut six minutes after coming on as a substitute. Following his return from suspension again having come on as a substitute it took just 17 seconds before he was sent off again.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/jun/10/football-trivia-liverpool-undefeated-seasons|title=The Knowledge: Have an undefeated team ever failed to win the title?|author=John Ashdown|work=the Guardian|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nPepper made just 15 appearances in league and cup for the club, but failed to find the net, in a period where on-field disciplinary problems haunted him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3A+Pepper%3A+Red+card+may+force+me+out.-a060360075|title=Football: Pepper: Red card may force me out.|publisher=|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Southend United===\nFollowing his unhappy time in Scotland, on 23 December 1999 Pepper joined [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] on loan for the remainder of the 1999/2000 season. He made a total of 12 appearances for The Seasiders, scoring 2 goals.\n\n===Scunthorpe United===\nAt the end of his contract with Aberdeen, Pepper signed for [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] on 7 June 2000 where he was immediately installed as club captain. However, in only his second game for the club against [[Kidderminster Harriers|Kidderminster]] he sustained a double leg fracture just 13 minutes into the game in a challenge with Paul Webb and despite the injuries Pepper retaliated at Webb earning him a red card while he was being stretchered off the pitch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisscunthorpe.co.uk/PAIN-INJURY-LIVES/story-11182367-detail/story.html|title=Pain of injury still lives on for ex-Scunthorpe United captain Nigel Pepper|work=Scunthorpe Telegraph|accessdate=10 February 2015}}{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/jan/18/what-is-the-fastest-goal-scored-by-a-football-team-not-kicking-off |title=The Knowledge |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=18 January 2017 |accessdate=1 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nPepper struggled for over a year to return to full fitness and although he made 1 further substitute appearance for the club he was released at the end of his contract in June 2002.\n\n===Barrow===\nIn 2004 Pepper joined non league Barrow.<ref>[http://www.scunthorpe-united.co.uk/page/News/0,,10442~222468,00.html Pepper Joins Barrow]</ref> He remained with the club until his retirement from football in 2008.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pepper, Nigel}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Rotherham]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Rotherham United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:York City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Aberdeen F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Southend United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scunthorpe United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Barrow A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Nigel Pepper\n| image = \n| fullname = Colin Nigel Pepper\n| height = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1968|4|25}}\n| birth_place = [[Rotherham]], England\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1986\u20131990 \n| years2 = 1990\u20131997 \n| years3 = 1997\u20131998 \n| years4 = 1998\u20132000 \n| years5 = 1999\u20132000 \n| years6 = 2000\u20132002 \n| years7 = 2002\u20132008\n| clubs1 = [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] \n| clubs2 = [[York City F.C.|York City]] \n| clubs3 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] \n| clubs4 = [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] \n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] (loan) \n| clubs6 = [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] \n| clubs7 = [[Barrow A.F.C.|Barrow]]\n| caps1 = 45   \n| caps2 = 235  \n| caps3 = 52  \n| caps4 = 14   \n| caps5 = 12   \n| caps6 = 3   \n| caps7 = ?   \n| goals1 = 1  \n| goals2 = 39  \n| goals3 = 11  \n| goals4 = 0  \n| goals5 = 2  \n| goals6 = 0  \n| goals7 = ?\n}}\n\n'''Colin Nigel Pepper''' (born 25 April 1968 in [[Rotherham]], England), more commonly known as '''Nigel Pepper''', is an English retired professional [[Association football|footballer]]. He was a combative midfield player known for his powerful attacking free kicks and his solid work ethic. He was a member of the [[York City F.C.|York City]] \nteam that beat [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] 3\u20130 at [[Old Trafford (football ground)|Old Trafford]] in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] in 1995.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Rotherham===\nPepper joined his hometown club [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] as an apprentice in 1985 when the club was playing in the old Division 3. He made his debut on 8 May 1986 at [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] aged just 17.<ref>[http://www.themillers.co.uk/staticFiles/87/1b/0,,10360~7047,00.doc Rotherham FC Players Factsheet] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208092603/http://www.themillers.co.uk/staticFiles/87/1b/0%2C%2C10360~7047%2C00.doc |date=8 February 2012 }}</ref> His first goal for the club came in a 3-2 [[Football League Cup|Littlewoods Cup]] defeat at [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].\n\nHis only league goal for the club came in a 4\u20132 home win against [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] on 25 November 1989, when he came on as substitute.\n\nHe remained at the club until 1990 and was a part of the side both relegated in 1988 and promoted in 1989.\n\n===York City===\nFollowing a lack of first team opportunities at Rotherham, Pepper signed for [[York City F.C.|York City]] on a free transfer on 18 July 1990.<ref name=\"sporting-heroes.net\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sporting-heroes.net/football/bradford-city-fc/nigel-pepper-9280/1996-97-1998-99_a17334|title=Sorry, the page was not found|publisher=|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref> He made his debut in the 1990\u201391 season against [[Maidstone United F.C. (1897)|Maidstone United]]. He helped the club secure promotion in 1992-93 scoring one of York's penalties in the [[1993 Football League Third Division play-off Final|1993 Playoff Final]] shootout victory at Wembley over [[Crewe Alexandra|Crewe]]. In that season he also took over as the clubs penalty taker and netted 19 out of 22 penalties between 1990\u20131997. He was also pivotal in York making the Playoff Semi-Finals the following season, although they did not secure promotion, losing 1-0 over two legs to [[Stockport County]].\n\nPepper was a member of the York team that beat [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] over two legs in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] in 1995. Having beaten a weakened United team 3\u20130 at [[Old Trafford (football ground)|Old Trafford]], York were beaten 3\u20131 at [[Bootham Crescent]] in the second leg but went through 4-3 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-484253/Red-faced-Manchester-Uniteds-cup-shocks-years.html|title=Red-faced: Manchester United's cup shocks over the years|work=Mail Online|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe following season, also in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]], Pepper played in the York side that defeated [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] 4-3 over two legs.\n\nHe made 281 league and cup appearances for the club, scoring 45 times.<ref>[http://www.yorkcityfootballclub.co.uk/players/n/nigel-pepper.php York City Profile]</ref> His final game for club came on 25 February 1997 when he scored in a 3\u20131 home win over [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston]].\n\n===Bradford City===\nPepper joined [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] on 28 February 1997 for a fee of \u00a3100,000.<ref name=\"sporting-heroes.net\"/> Bradford manager [[Chris Kamara]] brought him in to add some steel to his central midfield. He made his club debut on 1 March 1997 in a 3\u20131 defeat at home to [[Manchester City]]. He went on to make a total of 52 appearance for Bradford over 3 seasons in Division 1, scoring 11 goals and helping them avoid relegation.\n\n===Aberdeen===\nOn 26 November 1998 Pepper moved to [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] for a fee of \u00a3300,000.<ref name=\"sporting-heroes.net\"/> He did not enjoy the best of starts being sent off on his debut six minutes after coming on as a substitute. Following his return from suspension again having come on as a substitute it took just 17 seconds before he was sent off again.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/jun/10/football-trivia-liverpool-undefeated-seasons|title=The Knowledge: Have an undefeated team ever failed to win the title?|author=John Ashdown|work=the Guardian|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nPepper made just 15 appearances in league and cup for the club, but failed to find the net, in a period where on-field disciplinary problems haunted him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3A+Pepper%3A+Red+card+may+force+me+out.-a060360075|title=Football: Pepper: Red card may force me out.|publisher=|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Southend United===\nFollowing his unhappy time in Scotland, on 23 December 1999 Pepper joined [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] on loan for the remainder of the 1999/2000 season. He made a total of 12 appearances for The Seasiders, scoring 2 goals.\n\n===Scunthorpe United===\nAt the end of his contract with Aberdeen, Pepper signed for [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] on 7 June 2000 where he was immediately installed as club captain. However, in only his second game for the club against [[Kidderminster Harriers|Kidderminster]] he sustained a double leg fracture just 13 minutes into the game in a challenge with Paul Webb and despite the injuries Pepper retaliated at Webb earning him a red card while he was being stretchered off the pitch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisscunthorpe.co.uk/PAIN-INJURY-LIVES/story-11182367-detail/story.html|title=Pain of injury still lives on for ex-Scunthorpe United captain Nigel Pepper|work=Scunthorpe Telegraph|accessdate=10 February 2015}}{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/jan/18/what-is-the-fastest-goal-scored-by-a-football-team-not-kicking-off |title=The Knowledge |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=18 January 2017 |accessdate=1 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nPepper struggled for over a year to return to full fitness and although he made 1 further substitute appearance for the club he was released at the end of his contract in June 2002.\n\n===Barrow===\nIn 2004 Pepper joined non league Barrow.<ref>[http://www.scunthorpe-united.co.uk/page/News/0,,10442~222468,00.html Pepper Joins Barrow]</ref> He remained with the club until his retirement from football in 2008.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pepper, Nigel}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Rotherham]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Rotherham United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:York City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Aberdeen F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Southend United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scunthorpe United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Barrow A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eYork City:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1-0 \u2192 1\u20130 (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nigel_Pepper"}
